Your CPU runs in one of two relevant privilege levels. On x86-64 these are **ring 0** (kernel mode) and **ring 3** (user mode); other ISAs have analogous EL1/EL0 or supervisor/user modes. In ring 3 your code cannot touch hardware directly, cannot reprogram the MMU, and cannot execute privileged instructions — the same protection scheme you knew on radar hardware where only privileged firmware could poke certain registers. Everything else (browsers, compilers, your daemon) lives in ring 3.

When user code needs something only the kernel may do — read a file, allocate memory, send a packet — it cannot just jump into kernel code. That would defeat isolation. Instead it executes a **trap**: a single controlled instruction (`syscall` on x86-64, `svc` on ARM) that switches the CPU to ring 0 at *one fixed kernel entry point*. The kernel decides what to do based on a number you placed in a register.

```c
/* No stdio. A raw syscall: number in rax, args in rdi/rsi/rdx. */
#include <unistd.h>
int main(void) {
    write(1, "hi\n", 3);   /* __NR_write = 1 on x86-64 */
    return 0;
}
```

The argument count and order is the **syscall calling convention**, distinct from the C calling convention. The gateway is narrow on purpose: a fixed entry, a validated syscall number, and arguments the kernel must treat as untrusted. This single boundary — cross it deliberately or not at all — is the conceptual core of how Linux stays safe from the millions of lines of code running above it.

```bash
strace -e trace=write ./a.out   # see the one write() crossing the line
```

Behind the gateway the kernel is a multiplexer for shared resources. The big services it provides: **process scheduling** (deciding which thread runs on which CPU), **memory management** (virtual memory, paging, and the MMU translating per-process virtual addresses to physical frames — the same address-translation idea as a hardware page table), the **VFS** (one `open/read/write` interface over ext4, XFS, procfs, NFS, …), the **network stack** (TCP/IP, sockets), and **device drivers** that own the actual hardware.

You rarely issue raw `syscall` instructions. The **C library** (glibc on most distros, musl on Alpine/embedded) is a thin wrapper: `read()` in your code is a tiny libc stub that marshals arguments into registers, executes the trap, and converts the kernel's return into a C-friendly value plus `errno`. libc also adds buffering (stdio's `fread`), which is why one `printf` may not equal one `write`.

```c
#include <fcntl.h>
#include <unistd.h>
int fd = open("data.bin", O_RDONLY);   /* open + read + close: 3 syscalls */
char buf[4096];
ssize_t n = read(fd, buf, sizeof buf);
close(fd);
```

Distinguish **API** from **ABI**. The API is the source-level contract (function names, header types) you compile against. The **ABI** is the binary contract: which register holds which argument, struct layouts, the syscall numbers themselves. Linux famously keeps a stable syscall ABI — an old binary keeps working — even as APIs evolve.

Key syscall families to recognize: **process** (`fork`, `execve`, `wait4`, `exit`, `clone` — `clone` underlies both threads and container namespaces); **file** (`open`, `read`, `write`, `close`, `lseek`, `stat`, `mmap`); **IPC/sync** (`pipe`, `socket`, `shmget`, `futex` — the primitive under mutexes); **signals** (`kill`, `sigaction`, `rt_sigprocmask`).

```bash
strace -e trace=%process ./launcher   # watch fork/execve/wait4/clone
```

A **`.ko`** (kernel object) is compiled kernel code loaded into the running kernel's address space at runtime. Tooling:

```bash
lsmod                      # what's loaded (name, size, use count, dependents)
modinfo i2c_dev            # author, license, params, dependencies, vermagic
sudo insmod ./hello.ko     # raw load, no dep resolution
sudo modprobe i2c_dev      # resolves deps via modules.dep, searches /lib/modules
sudo rmmod hello           # unload (refcount must be 0)
sudo depmod                # rebuild modules.dep after installing modules
```

`modprobe` reads `/etc/modprobe.d/` for **parameters** (`options snd_hda_intel power_save=1`) and **blacklisting** (`blacklist nouveau`). Loading an out-of-tree or proprietary module sets the **taint** flag (see `dmesg`); maintainers ignore bug reports from a tainted kernel. A minimal module:

```c
#include <linux/module.h>
#include <linux/init.h>
static int __init hello_init(void){ printk(KERN_INFO "hello: loaded\n"); return 0; }
static void __exit hello_exit(void){ printk(KERN_INFO "hello: bye\n"); }
module_init(hello_init); module_exit(hello_exit);
MODULE_LICENSE("GPL");
```

Build it against your kernel headers with a one-line Makefile (`obj-m += hello.o`) and `make -C /lib/modules/$(uname -r)/build M=$PWD`, then `insmod` and read `dmesg`. Promote it to a **character driver**: define a `file_operations` struct (`.read`, `.write`, `.open`), then register either the old `register_chrdev()` or the modern **`cdev`** pair `alloc_chrdev_region()` + `cdev_init()` + `cdev_add()`:

```c
static struct file_operations fops = { .owner=THIS_MODULE, .read=my_read, .write=my_write };
```

For real hardware you go further: a **platform driver** matched to a node in the **device tree** (`of_match_table`) on its `compatible` string, then `ioremap()` the **MMIO** registers and `request_irq()` for interrupts -- exactly the radar/register-poking model, now inside the kernel. This connects directly to the embedded module later.

The **device tree (DT)** exists to solve one problem: most SoC peripherals are **not discoverable**. A USB or PCIe device can announce its vendor/product IDs, but an I2C temperature sensor wired to pins on your custom board cannot. Rather than hardcode every board into the kernel (the bad old ARM 'board files' era), Linux passes the kernel a **device tree blob (DTB)** describing the hardware as a tree of **nodes** and **properties**.

You write **`.dts`** source (and shared **`.dtsi`** include files for the SoC, included by board files) and compile it with the device-tree compiler **`dtc`** into a `.dtb`:

```dts
/dts-v1/;
#include "my-soc.dtsi"

&i2c1 {
    status = "okay";
    bmp280@76 {
        compatible = "bosch,bmp280";
        reg = <0x76>;        /* I2C address */
    };
};
```

The load-bearing property is **`compatible`**. The kernel matches a node's `compatible` string against each driver's `of_device_id` table; on a match the driver's `probe()` runs and binds to that node (this is exactly the platform/OF device model from Module 9). **A typo in the `compatible` string means no match, no probe, and a silent non-working peripheral** — the single most common DT bug.

```bash
dtc -I dts -O dtb -o board.dtb board.dts   # compile source to blob
dtc -I dtb -O dts -o out.dts board.dtb     # decompile to inspect
```

**Device-tree overlays** let you patch the base tree at runtime (e.g., enabling SPI or a GPIO LED on a Raspberry Pi) without recompiling the whole DTB — ideal for experimentation. Cardinal rule: edit the `.dts`, recompile, and redeploy the DTB. Never hand-edit the binary `.dtb`, and never forget to redeploy it after a change.
